english:
  title: A Gift for Yangok
  author: Jeong Do-jeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A wanderer has built a simple grass hut
    On the southern slope of that distant mountain.
    Sunlight falls upon its roof,
    And the grasses and trees gleam in its glow.

    His heart is empty and still, free from worldly striving,
    He sits in quiet repose, speaking of the I Ching's mysteries.
    See how one recovers in seven days—
    When friends arrive, neither illness nor harm touches them.

    Even before the ten thousand things took form,
    The mind of Heaven stood clear and true.
    Though change moves in endless directions,
    All transformations arise from that single source.

    This principle shines with perfect clarity—
    It has never been obscured since ancient times.
    Now I journey forth to inquire of it,
    But I ask you: teach me this once with careful words.
  footnotes:
    - The reference to recovery in seven days and freedom from illness likely alludes to Daoist practices of meditation and spiritual cultivation that promote longevity and health.
    - The I Ching (周易, Zhouyi) is the ancient Chinese Book of Changes, central to both Confucian and Daoist thought, here representing profound wisdom.
    - The 'mind of Heaven' (天心) refers to the underlying principle or order of the cosmos in Neo-Confucian philosophy, which Jeong Do-jeon deeply studied.
